tnership with the government, Making Failure Pay lays bare the unintended consequences of federal efforts to eliminate school failure—not the least of which is more failure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducation and statezUnited States. 0aEducationxStandardszUnited States. 0aEducational accountabilityzUnited States. 0aPrivatization in educationzUnited States. 0aPublic schoolszUnited States. 0aSchool improvement programsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aeducation policy, reform, no child left behind act, nclb, failing schools, after-school tutoring companies, for-profit corporations, federal funds, government intervention, regulation, educational standards, new york city, teachers, students, parents, testing, public ed, ethnographic fieldwork, political, politics, united states, policymakers, failure.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226451756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226451756/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles